  {
    "user": "U05UF5P8PT8",
    "type": "message",
    "ts": "1740077609.580349",
    "edited": {
      "user": "U05UF5P8PT8",
      "ts": "1740084494.000000"
    },
    "client_msg_id": "a498341e-54aa-4dea-9d45-9ad67eb44347",
    "text": "I disagree with the assertion that \"Visual programming hasn't been very successful\". I often see examples of visual programming systems that are used and appreciated by many people get discounted as merely domain specific - They aren't \"general purpose\".\n\nThis is a strange (and very common) default expectation of what programming languages should aspire to be. To me, this is a bit like discounting the effectiveness of a chain-saw, because it can't also be used as a screwdriver. We shouldn't judge visual programming languages based on their ability to be a  swiss-army-knife like the \"general purpose\" textual languages we have today.\n\nI'm not terribly interested in attempts at creating a \"general purpose\" visual programming languages. Designing a tool that can be used in EVERY domain seems hopelessly impossible. Designing a tool that works in a specific domain is going to be a lot more effective and achievable.",
    "team": "T5TCAFTA9",
    "thread_ts": "1740015637.601619",
    "parent_user_id": "U0378MDUG1Y",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "type": "rich_text",
        "block_id": "kVlW9",
        "elements": [
          {
            "type": "rich_text_section",
            "elements": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "I disagree with the assertion that \"Visual programming hasn't been very successful\". I often see examples of visual programming systems that are used and appreciated by many people get discounted as merely domain specific - They aren't \"general purpose\".\n\nThis is a strange (and very common) default expectation of what programming languages should aspire to be. To me, this is a bit like discounting the effectiveness of a chain-saw, because it can't also be used as a screwdriver. We shouldn't judge visual programming languages based on their ability to be a  swiss-army-knife like the \"general purpose\" textual languages we have today.\n\nI'm not terribly interested in attempts at creating a \"general purpose\" visual programming languages. Designing a tool that can be used in EVERY domain seems hopelessly impossible. Designing a tool that works in a specific domain is going to be a lot more effective and achievable."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      }
    ],
    "channel_name": "linking-together",
    "channel_id": "C5U3SEW6A"
  },
